- Precision, recall, and AUC are metrics used to evaluate the performance of machine learning models;
- A rating higher than 3 on a scale of 1 to 5 indicates a positive user experience;
- The area under the ROC curve (AUC) is a measure of a model's ability to distinguish between classes;
- "stands tall" is a metaphor for a model performing well across multiple metrics.

- "shining stars" refers to the top-performing models;
- "boasting the highest average accuracy" means the models with the highest average accuracy scores;
- "among all the models tested" indicates that the models are compared based on their test results.

- "Root mean square error (RMSE)" is a measure of the differences between values predicted by a model and the values actually observed;
- "Mean absolute error (MAE)" measures the average magnitude of the errors in a set of predictions, without considering their direction;
- "Regression models" are used to predict a continuous outcome variable based on one or more predictor variables.

- "Highest average test accuracy" refers to the model that performs best on average across multiple test instances;
- "Bloom with the most precision" is a metaphor for achieving high accuracy in predictions or classifications;
- "Garden of machine learning" is a metaphor for a collection or database of machine learning models.

- "Active models" refers to models with a status of 'active';
- "Growing" is a metaphor for the training process of the models;
- "Total time they have spent growing" refers to the sum of the durations of their training sessions.

